\newcounter{nbmDefinitionCounter}
% We test with the GCD function again, this time going to LaTeX
Wow this is LaTeX text.
Now we get this beautiful definition:
\begin{flalign*}
&\text{Define}~gcd : \mathbb{N} \times \mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{Z}^+~\text{by}&\\
&gcd\left(a, b\right) = \begin{cases}
  a, & \text{if}~b = 0\\
  gcd\left(b, a \bmod b\right), & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}&\\
&\text{where}~a \geq b.&
\end{flalign*}
And we can evaluate:
$gcd\left(12, 9\right) = 3$, $gcd\left(27, 14\right) = 1$ and $gcd\left(28, 14\right) = 14$.